a small but reproducible shared-output departure relative to the matched baseline.\\\\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:61:      - shared downstream readout\\\\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:75:    comparison: surface_wave/intact versus matched baseline/intact, then intact versus shuffled\\\\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:96:    comparison: (surface_wave/intact - baseline/intact) versus (surface_wave/shuffled - baseline/shuffled)\\\\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:101:      - matched baseline arm\\\\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:105:  - id: m1_survives_stronger_baseline\\\\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:106:    name: Survival against stronger reduced baseline P1\\\\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:107:    description: Confirm that the shared-output effect is not explained away by a stronger reduced baseline with explicit integration current or delay structure.\\\\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:115:    comparison: surface_wave/intact versus baseline P1/intact, with the same comparison available under shuffled topology\\\\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:116:    expected_relationship: The Milestone 1 effect remains detectable against P1, not only against P0.\\\\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:118:      - baseline P1 arm\\\\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:122:    notes: No numeric margin is locked yet; only the requirement that the effect survive the stronger reduced baseline.\\\\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:150:      description: Show point baseline and surface-wave model side by side on the same T4/T5-centered circuit.\\\\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:166:  - id: surface_vs_baseline_split_view\\\\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:168:    description: Side-by-side view of scalar baseline activity and distributed surface state for the same circuit and stimulus.\\\\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:169:    artifact_name: ui/surface_vs_baseline_split_view.json\\\\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:172:    description: Overlay of shared output traces for the matched surface-wave and baseline conditions.\\\\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:186:  - id: baseline_challenge_comparison\\\\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:188:    description: P0 versus P1 baseline challenge plot for the same observable family.\\\\nconfig/milestone_1_design_lock.yaml:189:    artifact_name: plots/baseline_challenge_comparison.png\\\\nconfig/local.yaml:51:        Add one-hop local context and direct downstream readout candidates while\\\\nconfig/visual_subset.example.yaml:74:        Add one-hop local context and direct downstream readout candidates while\\\\ndocs/operator_qa.md:148:- `go`: acceptable baseline for downstream solver and integration work\\\\ndocs/operator_qa.md:151:- `hold`: do not treat the operator bundle as a downstream baseline; rebuild or\\\\ndocs/milestones.md:55:- simulator software architecture  \\\\ndocs/milestones.md:68:- interpret readouts physically  \\\\ndocs/milestones.md:78:- interpret baseline vs wave differences  \\\\ndocs/milestones.md:95:| 9 | Build the baseline non-wave simulator | Programming-heavy (70/30) | Jack lead | Control model for comparison |\\\\ndocs/milestones.md:98:| 12 | Define readouts and task layer | Shared leaning math-physics (45/55) | Shared lead | Quantitative outputs and task metrics |\\\\ndocs/milestones.md:115: **Why it matters:** This prevents the project from becoming a cool visualization with no testable point, and locks the Milestone 1 scientific and artifact contract before the simulator is overbuilt.\\\\ndocs/milestones.md:123:**In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.**\\\\ndocs/milestones.md:133:* a shared downstream readout so comparison to baselines stays fair\\\\ndocs/milestones.md:140:* a decoder or readout unavailable to the baselines  \\\\ndocs/milestones.md:145:* **`P0`**: canonical point baseline using passive leaky linear non-spiking single-compartment neurons matched to the same circuit and readout  \\\\ndocs/milestones.md:146:* **`P1`**: stronger reduced baseline using an effective-point or reduced-compartment model with explicit synaptic integration current or explicit delay structure\\\\ndocs/milestones.md:151: In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.\\\\ndocs/milestones.md:153:**What should the wave model do differently than a baseline point-neuron model?**  \\\\ndocs/milestones.md:157: A geometry-sensitive shared-output effect, preferably on null-direction suppression or response latency, that survives a stronger reduced baseline.\\\\ndocs/milestones.md:167:* **Secondary shared readout:** direction selectivity index\\\\ndocs/milestones.md:172:* **Moderate:** the surface model changes a shared readout such as null-direction suppression, latency, or DSI  \\\\ndocs/milestones.md:173:* **Strong:** the shared-readout change shrinks or disappears when morphology or synapse topology is shuffled  \\\\ndocs/milestones.md:174:* **Very strong:** the effect survives the stronger reduced baseline `P1`\\\\ndocs/milestones.md:179:2. **`10–25 s`**: split screen with matched point baseline on the left and surface model on the right for the same T4/T5-centered circuit  \\\\ndocs/milestones.md:187:* split view showing baseline scalar activity versus surface-state activity on morphology  \\\\ndocs/milestones.md:192:* `P0` versus `P1` challenge-baseline comparison plot  \\\\ndocs/milestones.md:202:* Milestone 2+ simulator build-out beyond what is required to lock the design and output contract\\\\ndocs/milestones.md:229:* `P0` and `P1` baseline definitions are